content:
Certainly! To highlight all instances of the word "ubiquitous" in a given text on a webpage, you can use a combination of JavaScript and HTML. Here's a step-by-step guide along with the code to achieve this:

1. **Wrap the text in a container element**: First, you need to have your text inside an HTML element, like a `<div>` or `<p>`. This will allow you to manipulate its content.

2. **JavaScript function**: Create a JavaScript function that will search for the word "ubiquitous" and wrap each instance in a `<span>` tag with a specific background color.

3. **Execute the function**: Call the function to apply the highlighting.

Here's how you can implement it:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Highlight Text</title>
    <style>
        .highlight {
            background-color: yellow;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="content">
        The internet is ubiquitous in modern society. Its reach is ubiquitous, from cities to rural areas. The concept of the internet of things aims to make technology even more ubiquitous.
    </div>

    <script>
        function highlightWord(text, word) {
            // Create a regular expression to find all instances of the word
            const regex = new RegExp(`\\b${word}\\b`, 'gi');

            // Replace each instance with a span element for highlighting
            const highlightedText = text.replace(regex, `<span class="highlight">${word}</span>`);

            return highlightedText;
        }

        // Get the content element
        const contentElement = document.getElementById('content');

        // Get the original text
        const originalText = contentElement.innerHTML;

        // Highlight the word "ubiquitous"
        const highlightedContent = highlightWord(originalText, 'ubiquitous');

        // Update the content with the highlighted text
        contentElement.innerHTML = highlightedContent;
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:

- **Regular Expression**: The `\\b` in the regular expression `\\b${word}\\b` ensures that only whole words are matched (e.g., it won't match "ubiquitously").
- **`replace` method**: This method is used to replace each instance of "ubiquitous" with `<span class="highlight">ubiquitous</span>`, which applies the yellow background color.
- **Case Insensitivity**: The `i` flag in the regular expression makes the search case-insensitive, so it will match "Ubiquitous" as well as "ubiquitous".

You can run this code in an HTML file, and it will highlight all occurrences of the word "ubiquitous" with a yellow background.
